[[File:Holocene Temperature Variations.png|thumb|right|200px]]

'''Bond events''' are [[North Atlantic]] [[ice rafting]] events that are tentatively linked to climate fluctuations in the [[Holocene]]. Eight such events have been identified. Bond events were previously believed to exhibit a quasi c. 1,500-year cycle, but the primary period of variability is now put at c. 1,000 years.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Obrochta|first=Stephen P.|last2=Miyahara|first2=Hiroko|last3=Yokoyama|first3=Yusuke|last4=Crowley|first4=Thomas J.|date=2012-11-08|title=A re-examination of evidence for the North Atlantic “1500-year cycle” at Site 609|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0277379112003095|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|volume=55|pages=23–33|doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2012.08.008|bibcode=2012QSRv...55...23O}}</ref>

[[Gerard C. Bond]] of the [[Lamont–Doherty Earth Observatory]] at [[Columbia University]] was the lead author of the 1997 paper that postulated the theory of 1470-year climate cycles in the Late Pleistocene and Holocene, mainly based on [[petrologic]] tracers of drift ice in the North Atlantic.<ref name=":0">{{cite journal |last=Bond |first=G. |authorlink= |year=2001 |title=Persistent Solar Influence on North Atlantic Climate During the Holocene |journal=Science |volume=294 |issue=5549 |pages=2130–2136 |doi=10.1126/science.1065680 |url= |accessdate= |quote= |pmid=11739949 |bibcode = 2001Sci...294.2130B |display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref name="Bond1997">{{cite journal | author = Bond, G. | url = http://rivernet.ncsu.edu/courselocker/PaleoClimate/Bond%20et%20al.,%201997%20Millenial%20Scale%20Holocene%20Change.pdf | year = 1997 | title = A Pervasive Millennial-Scale Cycle in North Atlantic Holocene and Glacial Climates | journal = [[Science (journal)|Science]] | volume = 278 | issue = 5341 | pages = 1257–1266 | doi = 10.1126/science.278.5341.1257 | bibcode = 1997Sci...278.1257B | display-authors = etal | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080227192411/http://rivernet.ncsu.edu/courselocker/PaleoClimate/Bond%20et%20al.%2C%201997%20Millenial%20Scale%20Holocene%20Change.pdf | archivedate = 2008-02-27 | df =  }}</ref> However, more recent work has shown that these tracers provide little support for 1,500-year intervals of climate change, and the reported c. 1,500 ± 500-year period was a statistical artifact.<ref name=":1" /> Furthermore, following publication of the Greenland Ice Core Chronology 2005 (GICC05)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Svensson|first=A.|last2=Andersen|first2=K. K.|last3=Bigler|first3=M.|last4=Clausen|first4=H. B.|last5=Dahl-Jensen|first5=D.|last6=Davies|first6=S. M.|last7=Johnsen|first7=S. J.|last8=Muscheler|first8=R.|last9=Parrenin|first9=F.|date=2008-03-31|title=A 60 000 year Greenland stratigraphic ice core chronology|url=http://www.clim-past.net/4/47/2008/|journal=Clim. Past|volume=4|issue=1|pages=47–57|doi=10.5194/cp-4-47-2008|issn=1814-9332}}</ref> for the [[North Greenland Ice Core Project|North GRIP]] [[ice core]], it became clear that [[Dansgaard–Oeschger event]]s also show no such pattern.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ditlevsen|first=P. D.|last2=Andersen|first2=K. K.|last3=Svensson|first3=A.|date=2007-02-28|title=The DO-climate events are probably noise induced: statistical investigation of the claimed 1470 years cycle|url=http://www.clim-past.net/3/129/2007/|journal=Clim. Past|volume=3|issue=1|pages=129–134|doi=10.5194/cp-3-129-2007|issn=1814-9332}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Obrochta|first=Stephen P.|last2=Yokoyama|first2=Yusuke|last3=Morén|first3=Jan|last4=Crowley|first4=Thomas J.|date=2014-04-01|title=Conversion of GISP2-based sediment core age models to the GICC05 extended chronology|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1871101413000745|journal=Quaternary Geochronology|volume=20|pages=1–7|doi=10.1016/j.quageo.2013.09.001}}</ref> The North Atlantic [[ice-rafting]] events happen to correlate with episodes of lowered lake levels in the  Mid-Atlantic region, USA,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Li|first=Yong-Xiang|last2=Yu|first2=Zicheng|last3=Kodama|first3=Kenneth P.|year=2007|title=Sensitive moisture response to Holocene millennial-scale climate variations in the Mid-Atlantic region, USA|url=|journal=The Holocene|volume=17 | issue = 1 |pages=3–8|doi=10.1177/0959683606069386|via=}}</ref> the weakest{{clarify|date=February 2017}} events of the [[Asia]]n [[monsoon]] for at least the past 9,000 years,<ref>{{cite journal | last = Gupta | first = Anil K. | authorlink = |author2=Anderson, David M. |author3=Overpeck, Jonathan T. | year = 2003 | title = Abrupt changes in the Asian southwest monsoon during the Holocene and their links to the North Atlantic Ocean | journal = Nature | volume = 421 | issue = 6921 | pages = 354–357 | doi = 10.1038/nature01340 | url = | accessdate = | quote = | pmid = 12540924 |bibcode = 2003Natur.421..354G }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Yongjin Wang |year=2005 |title=The Holocene Asian Monsoon: Links to Solar Changes and North Atlantic Climate |journal=Science |volume=308 |issue=5723 |pages=854–857 |doi=10.1126/science.1106296 |url= |accessdate= |quote= |pmid=15879216 |bibcode = 2005Sci...308..854W |display-authors=etal}}</ref> and also correlate with most aridification events in the [[Middle East]] for the past 55,000 years (both [[Heinrich event|Heinrich]] and Bond events).<ref>{{cite journal |last=Bartov |first=Yuval |last2=Goldstein |first2=Steven L. |last3=Stein |first3=Mordechai |last4=Enzel |first4=Yehouda |year=2003|title=Catastrophic arid episodes in the Eastern Mediterranean linked with the North Atlantic Heinrich events |journal=[[Geology (journal)|Geology]] |volume=31 |issue=5 |pages=439–442 |doi=10.1130/0091-7613(2003)031<0439:CAEITE>2.0.CO;2 |bibcode = 2003Geo....31..439B }}</ref><ref name="Parker2006">{{cite journal | last = Parker | first = Adrian G. | year = 2006 | title = A record of Holocene climate change from lake geochemical analyses in southeastern Arabia | journal = Quaternary Research | volume = 66 | issue = 3 | pages = 465–476 | doi = 10.1016/j.yqres.2006.07.001 | url = | display-authors = 1 | last2 = Goudie | first2 = A | last3 = Stokes | first3 = S | last4 = White | first4 = K | last5 = Hodson | first5 = M | last6 = Manning | first6 = M | last7 = Kennet | first7 = D   |bibcode = 2006QuRes..66..465P }}</ref>

For reasons that are unclear, the only Holocene Bond event that has a clear temperature signal in the Greenland ice cores is the [[8.2 kiloyear event]].{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}

==List==
Most Bond events do not have a clear climate signal; some correspond to periods of cooling, but others are coincident with aridification in some regions.

