{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}} '''Midnight Volcano''' is a buried [[Extinct Volcano|extinct volcano]] near [[Midnight, Mississippi]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cdispatch.com/opinions/article.asp?aid=47721|title=Ask Rufus: Tombigbee sharks and Mississippi volcanoes|work=The Commercial Dispatch|access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref> in southern [[Humphreys County, Mississippi|Humphreys County]]. The volcano was last active in the [[Late Cretaceous]] period and is associated with the volcanic activity of the [[Monroe Uplift]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdeq.ms.gov/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Bulletin-85.pdf|title=Cretaceous Shelf Sediments of Mississippi, Mississippi State Geological Survey, Bulletin 85|last=Mellen|first=Frederic Francis|date=April 18, 1958|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsouthernview.com/pages/nsv_wht_jacksons_volcano.html|title=NSV Whatever Happened To...?|last=Pitts|first=Bill|date=|website=www.newsouthernview.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref> which occurred around 80 million years ago. The [[Jackson Volcano]], southeast of Midnight, was active around 10 million years later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.lsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=5932&context=gradschool_disstheses|title=Petrogenesis and Provenance of Epiclastic Volcanic Cobbles From the Cretaceous Woodbine Formation, Southwest Arkansas.|last=Livesey|first=Christina Lee|date=1990|website=|series=LSU Historical Dissertations and Theses 4933|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=11 November 2018}}</ref> Volcanic debris from Midnight or other volcanoes of the Monroe Uplift were found in the "Coffee sand," a Cretaceous sand layer to the north of the volcano.
