{{Energy-stub}}

'''Suffosion''' is one of the two [[geology|geological]] processes by which [[subsidence]] [[sinkhole]]s or dolines are formed, the other being due to collapse of an underlying [[cave]] or void,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sinkholes and Subsidence|last1=Waltham|first1=T.|last2=Bell|first2=T.|last3=Culshaw|first3=M.|publisher=Berlin: Springer|year=2005|isbn=978-3540207252}}</ref> with most sinkholes formed by the suffosion process.<ref name="BGS">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bgs.ac.uk/mendips/caveskarst/karst_3.htm|title=Dolines and sinkholes|publisher=[[British Geological Survey]]|accessdate=February 21, 2011}}</ref> Suffosion sinkholes are normally associated with [[karst topography]] although they may form in other types of rock including [[chalk]], [[gypsum]] and [[basalt]]. In the karst of the UK's [[Yorkshire Dales]], numerous surface depressions known locally as "shakeholes" are the result of [[Till|glacial till]] washing into fissures in the underlying limestone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://science.jrank.org/pages/47693/ground-subsidence.html|title=Ground Subsidence|author=Waltham, T.|accessdate=February 21, 2011}}</ref>
[[File:SuffosionSinkholeFormation.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Formation of a suffosion sinkhole]]
==Process== Suffosion occurs when loose soil, [[loess]], or other non-cohesive material lies on top of a limestone substratum containing fissures and joints. Rain and surface water gradually wash this material through these fissures and into caves beneath.<ref name="BGS" /> Over time, this creates a depression on the landscape of varying depth.
==Examples== {{Expand section|date=February 2011}} The following sites are examples of sinkholes formed by suffosion: *Whitepit, south of [[Priddy]], Somerset, UK;
