==Production==
{{Expand section|1=I just added this section. Many sources already used go into these details. Feel free to help me expand it.|section=1|date=November 2018}} <!-- Please refer to [[MOS:FILM]] Wikiproject Film style guide. Refer to section on production and section on documentaries. -->
Initially commissioned by French government-owned television to create a two part made for TV documentary,<ref name="Busi" />{{When|date=November 2018}} the film was banned after Olphus submitted it to the studio that hired him.<ref name="Jeffries-Guardian" />

==Release==
<!-- While reading about the film and adding details to the article I've inadvertently nested things that belong under reception in response to what was already written here. This section needs to be reworked as well -->The film "had its world premiere in Germany."<ref name="Busi" />{{When|date=November 2018}} This film was first shown on French television in 1981<ref name="Jeffries-Guardian" /> after being banned<ref name="Liebenson" /> from that medium for years. In 1969, after the director submitted the film to the studio that hired him, the network head "told a government committee that the film 'destroys myths that the people of France still need'."<ref name="Jeffries-Guardian">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/jan/23/1|title=A nation shamed: Why does France keep making films that glorify the Resistance and gloss over the truth about collaboration?|last1=Jeffries|first1=Stuart|date=January 22, 2004|work=The Guardian|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref> Frederick Busi suggests that this was because of how uncomfortable it is to face the reality of collaborationism. Writing of French conservative establishment groups' reactions to the film, "They, too, preferred that little be said about their role, and in some ways this reluctance is more significant than that of the extremists, since they represent so large a segment of society and mainly dominate contemporary politics."<ref name="Busi"/>  It is frequently assumed that the reason was French reluctance to admit the facts of French history. While this may have been a factor, the principal mover in the decision was [[Simone Veil]], a Jewish inmate of Auschwitz who became a minister and the first president of the European Parliament, on the grounds that the film presented too one-sided a view.<ref>Simone Veil, ''Mémoires'', Paris, 2008</ref>{{Clarify|date=September 2018}}

==Reception==
<!-- This needs to be reorded chronologically ending with the awards list. -->The candid approach of the 1971 documentary ''The Sorrow and the Pity'' shone a spotlight on antisemitism in France and disputed the official Resistance ideals.<ref name="Weitz">{{Cite book |last=Weitz |first=Margaret Collins |title=Sisters in the Resistance – How Women Fought to Free France 1940–1945 |year=1995 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Inc |location=New York |isbn=978-0-471-19698-3 |ref=harv|page=13}}</ref><ref name="Greene">{{Cite book |last=Greene |first=Naomi |title= Landscapes of Loss: The National Past in Postwar French Cinema |year=1999 |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=New Jersey |isbn=978-0-691-00475-4 |ref=harv|page=69–73}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine gave a positive review of the film, and wrote that Marcel Ophüls "tries to puncture the bourgeois myth—or protectively askew memory—that allows France generally to act as if hardly any Frenchmen collaborated with the Germans."<ref>{{Cite journal|author=|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,910312,00.html |title=TIME magazine: Truth and Consequences |journal=Time |date=1972-03-27 |accessdate=2012-08-27}}</ref> In France, after its release, communists, socialists, and "independent groups" treated the film favorably, however, the far right disapproved on account of the director's background.<ref name="Busi" /> Some{{who|date=November 2018}} denounced the film as unpatriotic.<ref name="Jeffries-Guardian" /> The film has also been criticized for being too selective and that the director was "too close to the events portrayed to provide an objective study of the period."<ref name="Busi" /><ref name="Hoffman">{{Cite news|url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/articles/on-the-sorrow-and-the-pity/|title=On 'The Sorrow and the Pity'|last=Hoffman|first=Stanley|work=Commentary|access-date=November 3, 2018|year=1972}}
</ref> In 2001, Richard Trank, a documentarian of the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]], described it as "a film about morality that explores the role of ordinary people."<ref name="Liebenson" /> It was nominated for an [[Academy Award]] in 1971 for [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]].<ref name="NY Times">{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/45714/Le-Chagrin-et-la-Pitie/details|title=Le Chagrin et la Pitie - Cast, Crew, Director and Awards|last=|first=|date=n.d.|work=New York Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519054324/https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/45714/Le-Chagrin-et-la-Pitie/details|archive-date=May 19, 2009|dead-url=yes|accessdate=November 12, 2008|quote=Win Special Award - 1972 New York Film Critics Circle Best Foreign Film - 1972 National Board of Review Nomination Best Documentary Feature - 1971 Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences}}</ref><ref name="academy">{{Cite web |url=http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/BasicSearch?action=searchLink&displayType=1&BSFromYear=44 |title=The Official Acadademy Awards® Database |access-date=November 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130415143109/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/BasicSearch?action=searchLink&displayType=1&BSFromYear=44 |archive-date=2013-04-15 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref name="Petrakis" /> It won "the Grand Prize of the {{ill|Dinard Festival|fr|Festival du film britannique de Dinard}}".<ref name="Busi">{{Cite journal|last=Busi|first=Frederick|date=Winter 1973|title=Marcel Ophuls and the Sorrow and the Pity|journal=The Massachusetts Review|volume=14|issue=1|pages=177–186|jstor=25088330}}</ref>{{When|date=November 2018}} It received "a special award by the National Society of Film Critics, which called it 'a film of extraordinary public interest and distinction.'"<ref name="Liebenson" />{{When|date=November 2018}}

==In popular culture==
[[Woody Allen]]'s film ''[[Annie Hall]]'' (1977) makes two references to ''The Sorrow and the Pity'' as "a gag line" because of its long running time.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dailyscript.com/scripts/annie_hall.html | title = ''Annie Hall'' Film Script | publisher = DailyScript.com | accessdate = 2015-01-27}}</ref><ref name="Petrakis">{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2000-07-14-0007140296-story.html|title='Sorrow' a Complete Look at how the French Dealt with the Nazis|last=Petrakis|first=John|date=July 14, 2000|work=Chicago Tribune|access-date=November 3, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Liebenson">{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/jan/19/entertainment/ca-14035|title=A Look at 'The Sorrow and the Pity' of France in World War II|last=Liebenson|first=Donald|date=January 19, 2001|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=November 3, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Turan">{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/jul/07/entertainment/ca-48843|title='Sorrow and the Pity' Still Potent, Powerful|last=Turan|first=Kenneth|date=July 7, 2000|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=November 4, 2018}}</ref>

